70 THE CHILD OF THE POEM

Lucina: and then again, as the fateful moment approacheS, she eries, Aggredere 0 magnos, aderit iam tempus, honores: now the child lies before her, and the sight brings her back to the human and the present. It seems to me that the poem gains immensely in truth and beauty, showing us the true Virgilian tenderness and pity, if we look at it in this clear and undistorted light.

.I have said that the vates now uses the language of the Italian nurse. No one has seen this so clearly, I think, as Mr R. C. Scaton, in a short paper contributed to the Classical Review in 1893 (p. 199); and he has also come near to reaching what l believe to be the true meaning of the last line oi all, which has baffled the commentators ever since it was written.
